28 11 multis . . . ante saeculis: these words are more than a mere digression, for they touch upon one of the unsettled literary questions of Cicero's time and earlier— the chronological relation of Homer to Hesiod. Accius, one of the most important critics before Cicero’s time, put Hesiod first: M. autem Varro, in primo de Imaginibus, uter prior sit natus parum constare dicit . . . Accius autem, in primo Didascalico, levi· bus admodum argumentis· utitur per quae ostendi putat Hesiodum natu priorem (Aul. Gell. 3, 11, 3). — Laertam: Laertes, father of Ulysses (Od. 24, 225). The desiderium is for the long absence of his son at the siege of Troy, and during his Subsequent wanderingS. Homer does not represent him as stercorantem, but as digging (λιστρεύοντα), which in Cicero’s mind might include the other.
